            <p class="text-xl text-vagus-dark font-medium leading-relaxed">Optimization isn't about doing more; it's about doing the right things at the right time. Your Vagus Nerve operates on a circadian rhythm, and by aligning your practices with this internal clock, you can achieve far greater results with less effort.</p>

            <p>If you're already experiencing <a href="/symptoms" class="text-vagus-blue font-bold hover:underline">Vagus Nerve dysfunction symptoms</a>, this planner is your roadmap to recovery. It integrates <a href="/priming" class="text-vagus-blue font-bold hover:underline">morning priming</a>, midday resets, and evening shutdowns into a cohesive system.</p>

            <!-- Morning Section -->
            <div class="bg-vagus-soft rounded-[2rem] p-8 md:p-12 border border-vagus-border shadow-sm space-y-6">
                <div class="flex items-center gap-4">
                    <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-vagus-primary text-white rounded-2xl flex items-center justify-center shadow-lg">
                        <svg class="w-6 h-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 3v1m0 16v1m9-9h-1M4 12H3m15.364-6.364l-.707.707M6.343 17.657l-.707.707m12.728 0l-.707-.707M6.343 6.343l-.707-.707M12 5a7 7 0 100 14 7 7 0 000-14z"/></svg>
                    </div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-vagus-dark m-0">Phase 1: Morning Activation (6–9 AM)</h2>
                </div>
                <p>The goal of the morning is to signal "safety" to the brain while gently awakening the nervous system. Cortisol is naturally high, so we want to channel that energy without triggering anxiety.</p>
                <ul class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                    <li class="flex gap-3">
                        <span class="text-vagus-blue font-bold">06:30</span>
                        <span>**Cold Exposure**: 30-second cold face splash or shower to trigger the mammalian dive reflex.</span>
                    </li>
                    <li class="flex gap-3">
                        <span class="text-vagus-blue font-bold">07:00</span>
                        <span>**Breathwork**: 5 minutes of box breathing (4-4-4-4) to stabilize HRV.</span>
                    </li>
                    <li class="flex gap-3">
                        <span class="text-vagus-blue font-bold">07:30</span>
                        <span>**Priming**: Gentle neck stretches and vocal toning (humming) while preparing breakfast.</span>
                    </li>
                    <li class="flex gap-3">
                        <span class="text-vagus-blue font-bold">08:00</span>
                        <span>**Light Movement**: A 10-minute walk to get natural sunlight into the eyes.</span>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <!-- Midday Section -->
            <div class="bg-white rounded-[2rem] p-8 md:p-12 border border-vagus-border shadow-sm space-y-6">
                <div class="flex items-center gap-4">
                    <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-vagus-blue text-white rounded-2xl flex items-center justify-center shadow-lg">
                        <svg class="w-6 h-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8v4l3 3m6-3a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg>
                    </div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-vagus-dark m-0">Phase 2: Midday Reset (12–2 PM)</h2>
                </div>
                <p>Midday is the most common time for a "nervous system crash." By performing a mini-reset, you can avoid the 3 PM slump and maintain high cognitive function.</p>
                <ul class="space-y-4">
                    <li>**Mindful Eating**: No screens while eating. Focus on chewing slowly—this stimulates the cephalic phase of digestion via the Vagus Nerve.</li>
                    <li>**The 2-Minute Reset**: Close your eyes and perform three "physiological sighs" (two inhales through the nose, one long exhale through the mouth).</li>
                    <li>**Social Connection**: Briefly talk to a friend or colleague. Positive social engagement is a powerful vagal stimulator.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <!-- Evening Section -->
            <div class="bg-vagus-dark text-white rounded-[2rem] p-8 md:p-12 shadow-2xl space-y-6 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute bottom-0 right-0 w-64 h-64 bg-vagus-primary/10 rounded-full -mr-32 -mb-32 blur-3xl"></div>
                <div class="flex items-center gap-4 relative">
                    <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-white text-vagus-dark rounded-2xl flex items-center justify-center shadow-lg">
                        <svg class="w-6 h-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M20.354 15.354A9 9 0 018.646 3.646 9.003 9.003 0 0012 21a9.003 9.003 0 008.354-5.646z"/></svg>
                    </div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold m-0">Phase 3: Evening Shutdown (6–10 PM)</h2>
                </div>
                <p class="opacity-90">This is where we transition into deep <a href="/sleep" class="text-vagus-primary font-bold hover:underline">Sleep Hypnosis</a> mode. We want to eliminate all sympathetic "noise."</p>
                <ul class="space-y-4 opacity-90">
                    <li>**Gargling/Humming**: 2 minutes of vigorous gargling with water or loud humming to stimulate the laryngeal branches.</li>
                    <li>**Tech Shutdown**: Blue light off by 8:30 PM. Blue light suppresses the Vagus-Melatonin connection.</li>
                    <li>**Pillow Speaker Setup**: Load your <a href="/sleep" class="text-vagus-primary font-bold hover:underline">Sleep Hypnosis audio</a> and prepare for a phone-free night.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-vagus-dark pt-8 border-b border-vagus-border pb-4">Consistency is Your Only Metric</h2>
            <p>You don't need to be perfect. If you only hit Phase 1 today, that's a win. The Vagus Nerve responds to consistency over intensity. For a deeper dive into the tools mentioned here, check out our <a href="/top-products" class="text-vagus-blue font-bold hover:underline">Top Recommended Products</a> list.</p>

